WEBVTT

00:00:00.640 --> 00:00:05.760
Hi, my name is James Blair and I'm a Senior Product Manager at Posit over Cloud Integrations.

00:00:06.400 --> 00:00:10.640
Today we're going to walk through a demo of using the R language to analyze and explore

00:00:10.640 --> 00:00:15.360
data that's stored in Snowflake. We will do this by setting up an R environment inside

00:00:15.360 --> 00:00:19.760
of Posit Workbench that's running as a native app on Snowpark Container Services.

00:00:20.559 --> 00:00:26.160
We will also explore how using the R, dbplyr interface can be used to push computation

00:00:26.160 --> 00:00:30.320
into Snowflake so that you have access to greater memory and compute resources than

00:00:30.320 --> 00:00:34.160
you typically would have in a standard R session. Let's get started.

00:00:36.400 --> 00:00:41.520
The first thing we need to do is gain access to our data. Luckily, Snowflake makes this very easy

00:00:41.520 --> 00:00:46.320
through the Marketplace. If we go to Data Products inside of Snowflake and then the Marketplace,

00:00:46.320 --> 00:00:50.400
we can search for different providers. In our case, we're going to look for Cybersyn.

00:00:51.200 --> 00:00:55.200
Cybersyn offers a number of different data assets on the Snowflake Marketplace,

00:00:55.200 --> 00:00:58.639
but we're going to scroll down and we're going to look for the Web Traffic dataset.

00:01:01.599 --> 00:01:04.639
Here we can see the Web Traffic Foundation Experimental dataset,

00:01:04.639 --> 00:01:08.959
select it. I've already subscribed to this dataset, so I have the option to open it,

00:01:08.959 --> 00:01:13.279
but if this is the first time you've gone through this process, you would select the option to get

00:01:13.279 --> 00:01:18.480
this dataset. Now that this dataset is configured and we have access to it through Snowflake,

00:01:19.360 --> 00:01:24.160
we need to open up Posit Workbench. Posit Workbench within Snowpark Container Services

00:01:24.160 --> 00:01:28.559
can be set up and configured by a Snowflake administrator. Once that service has been

00:01:28.559 --> 00:01:32.879
configured, the administrator can share a URL with you that gives you access to the service.

00:01:33.839 --> 00:01:38.639
Here we'll open Posit Workbench and notice that this is running inside of Snowflake.

00:01:39.680 --> 00:01:43.839
The first thing that we need to do here is create a new session. I'll click on the New Session

00:01:43.839 --> 00:01:48.800
button, choose RStudio Pro, and then you'll notice that I have an option to sign in to my

00:01:48.800 --> 00:01:53.519
current Snowflake account. I'll click Sign In. This will bring me to a page where I can enter

00:01:53.519 --> 00:01:58.720
my Snowflake credentials and then verify that this is signing into the account with the role

00:01:58.720 --> 00:02:05.120
that I want it to use. Once I click Allow, I'll be notified that I can close this window and come

00:02:05.120 --> 00:02:10.000
back to my session for RStudio. Here I can see that I'm now signed in to this Snowflake account

00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:19.919
and I can click Start Session. Once our RStudio session is opened, we need to gain access to the

00:02:19.919 --> 00:02:24.479
code that we're going to walk through. This code is made available in a GitHub repository.

00:02:25.119 --> 00:02:33.039
I'm going to visit the repository, choose the code to clone this repository using HTTPS,

00:02:33.759 --> 00:02:39.039
and then come back into RStudio. Here inside of RStudio, I can now create a new project.

00:02:40.320 --> 00:02:47.119
Using version control from Git, and then copy and paste the URL from the repository into here.

00:02:47.759 --> 00:02:48.639
We'll give this a name.

00:02:52.320 --> 00:02:55.919
I'll choose the R version that I want to use and we'll create our project.

00:03:02.160 --> 00:03:07.119
Now that our project is open, we have a Cordo document that we can open that contains code

00:03:07.119 --> 00:03:10.639
that allows us to connect to and work with the data contained in Snowflake.

00:03:11.199 --> 00:03:15.440
The first thing we're going to do is load some of the R packages we need into our R session.

00:03:17.360 --> 00:03:22.399
Once our packages are loaded, we can connect directly to Snowflake using the dbconnect function

00:03:22.399 --> 00:03:27.199
from the dbi package. Notice that in order to create this connection, we didn't have to supply

00:03:27.199 --> 00:03:32.160
any additional credentials, details, or authentication information because when we

00:03:32.160 --> 00:03:36.720
signed in to Posit Workbench, we signed directly into our Snowflake warehouse.

00:03:36.720 --> 00:03:41.919
This allows Posit Workbench to supply credentials for us when we make these connections into

00:03:41.919 --> 00:03:46.639
Snowflake. This is both easier for the developer and more secure when it comes to connecting to

00:03:46.639 --> 00:03:51.360
Snowflake data. Now we can create references to two tables that are contained within the

00:03:51.360 --> 00:03:58.559
Cybersyn dataset that we gained access to earlier. Now that we've created these two

00:03:59.199 --> 00:04:02.880
objects, time series and attributes, we're going to do some slight data cleaning

00:04:03.600 --> 00:04:06.559
and combine the two into a single object called time series.

00:04:10.639 --> 00:04:14.160
One of the things that's unique about the way that we've connected to Snowflake here is that

00:04:14.160 --> 00:04:18.720
this time series object does not represent data that's stored in local memory inside of our R

00:04:18.720 --> 00:04:24.399
Studio session, but instead it represents a SQL query that needs to be executed against Snowflake

00:04:24.399 --> 00:04:28.079
in order to create the view or the object that we're referencing here.

00:04:28.799 --> 00:04:33.679
To show an example of this, if we use the show query function against time series,

00:04:35.440 --> 00:04:40.480
we can see the SQL statement that will be executed in order to create this object within Snowflake.

00:04:42.720 --> 00:04:46.720
Now let's take a look at some of the top web domains from this web traffic dataset that

00:04:46.720 --> 00:04:54.559
we've collected. If we filter our data to include only the domains that we've listed,

00:04:54.559 --> 00:04:57.440
we can now create a final view of this data

00:05:00.320 --> 00:05:07.200
that will allow us to visualize and analyze web traffic to these select domains. Here's a view of

00:05:07.200 --> 00:05:13.519
what that final data will look like. Notice that in this final version of the data, we have each

00:05:13.519 --> 00:05:19.519
domain, a date, the number of page views, users, and sessions. All of this was done while keeping

00:05:19.519 --> 00:05:24.720
all the data inside of Snowflake and using the dbplyr interface from R to analyze and work with

00:05:24.720 --> 00:05:30.000
that data. Now that we have our data in this final form, we can create some compelling visualizations.

00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:38.160
For example, comparing web traffic to Airbnb and VRBO. We can do this using ggplot, which will

00:05:38.160 --> 00:05:44.880
result in a graphic that shows the comparison between VRBO traffic and Airbnb traffic since 2021.

00:05:47.760 --> 00:05:50.640
We can also use the GT package to create a summary table

00:05:51.200 --> 00:05:55.600
that contains some summary statistics about the different domains that we have access to.

00:06:01.119 --> 00:06:05.359
Here's an example that shows each domain and the number of page views,

00:06:05.359 --> 00:06:09.040
users, and sessions with a highlight on Airbnb and VRBO.

00:06:12.079 --> 00:06:16.559
Finally, let's do some marketing analysis. There are two main ratios that we might be interested in.

00:06:16.559 --> 00:06:20.959
Content engagement, which is the number of page views compared to users, and repeat rates and

00:06:20.959 --> 00:06:27.040
website usage, the number of sessions compared to the number of users. We can calculate this for all

00:06:27.040 --> 00:06:30.559
per session for all the domains that we have by running the following code.

00:06:30.799 --> 00:06:34.559
We can then take this code and this final table that we've created called marketing

00:06:35.359 --> 00:06:41.760
and visualize it using ggplot. This graphic that's been created now shows marketing ratios

00:06:41.760 --> 00:06:46.000
over time for each of the select domains that we've chosen from our web traffic data set.

00:06:48.480 --> 00:06:53.040
Before we conclude, let's take a look at one more thing. If we go back to the files pane inside of

00:06:53.279 --> 00:06:56.239
If we go back to the files pane inside of VR Studio IDE,

00:06:57.920 --> 00:07:03.359
there's a folder called app. Inside this folder is an app.r file that contains a Shiny application

00:07:03.359 --> 00:07:07.200
that creates an interactive application for real-time exploration of this data set.

00:07:08.079 --> 00:07:11.920
This application uses many of the same principles that we just outlined in the

00:07:11.920 --> 00:07:20.720
Cordo document. If we select run app here, this will create an interactive application

00:07:20.720 --> 00:07:25.760
running on top of data inside of Snowflake that allows us to explore and investigate

00:07:25.760 --> 00:07:31.359
different comparisons across different web traffic domains. Here we're comparing Facebook and Google,

00:07:31.359 --> 00:07:36.880
but we could change this to be Facebook and Instagram, and we can see that the plot and

00:07:36.880 --> 00:07:41.679
the page update as a result of the selections that are made here, all backed by queries that

00:07:41.679 --> 00:07:48.320
are being submitted in real-time to our Snowflake data warehouse. As we've seen today, R is a powerful

00:07:48.399 --> 00:07:53.440
language for interactive data analysis and exploration. We've demonstrated how you can use

00:07:53.440 --> 00:07:59.519
RStudio within Posit Workbench running on top of Snowpark container services in order to securely

00:07:59.519 --> 00:08:05.600
and quickly access data inside of a Snowflake data warehouse. This interaction speeds up the ability

00:08:05.600 --> 00:08:10.239
of data scientists to arrive at meaningful business insights using data that's securely

00:08:10.239 --> 00:08:16.239
governed within Snowflake. We focused today on using the RStudio IDE within Posit Workbench,

00:08:16.239 --> 00:08:20.720
but as we saw earlier, Posit Workbench also supports other environments like VS Code and

00:08:20.720 --> 00:08:25.760
Jupyter-based environments for data scientists who may prefer to work within languages like Python.

00:08:26.559 --> 00:08:29.040
We hope you've enjoyed the demo today, and thank you for watching.

